bib.title: -MICROSCOPIC AND CONVENTIONAL OPTICAL MODEL ANALYSIS OF NEUTRON ELASTIC SCATTERING AT 21.6 MEV OVER A WIDE MASS RANGE.

free_txt: STUDSVIK 6 MV VAN DE GRAAFF ACCELERATOR,
EQUIPPED WITH A TERMINAL PULSING AND KLYSTRON BUNCHING
SYSTEM, AS WELL AS A POST-ACCELERATION BUNCHER.
DELIVERS BURSTS OF IONS AT A REPETITION RATE OF 1 MHZ
WITH A PULSE WIDTH AT HALF MAXIMUM OF LESS THAN 0.3 NS
AND AN AVERAGE BEAM CURRENT OF 3 MICROAMPS.
N.O.
PHENOMENOLOGIC AND MICROSCOPIC OPTICAL MODEL
PARAMETERS DETERMINED.
.CORRECTIONS WERE APPLIED FOR THE VARIATION OF THE
DETECTOR EFFICIENCY WITH ENERGY, ANISOTROPY OF THE
NEUTRONS FROM THE D-T REACTION, FINITE SCATTERING
GEOMETRY, FLUX ATTENUATION IN THE SCATTERING SAMPLES
AND MULTIPLE SCATTERING. A MONTE CARLO PROGRAM WAS
USED TO TREAT THE LATTER THREE EFFECTS.
.ZERO-DEGREE DIRECTION DETERMINED BY MEASURING THE
SCATTERED YIELD ON BOTH SIDES OF THIS DIRECTION.
TWO IDENTICAL 12.7 CM DIAMETER BY 5.1 CM THICK
NE 213 LIQUID SCINTILLATORS, MOUNTED ON FAST PHOTO-
MULTIPLIER TUBES, WERE USED TO MEASURE THE ANGULAR
DISTRIBUTIONS OF SCATTERED NEUTRONS. THE DETECTORS
WERE SEPARATED BY AN ANGLE OF 5 DEGREES IN THE
AZIMUTHAL PLANE AND WERE POSITIONED AT A DISTANCE OF
4 M FROM THE SCATTERING SAMPLE IN A HEAVY SHIELDING.
WITH A LOWER LEVEL DISCRIMINATOR SET AT 3 MEV NEUTRON
ENERGY, EXCELLENT N-GAMMA DISCRIMINATION AND INTRIN-
SIC TIME RESOLUTION, 0.5 NS FWHM, WAS OBTAINED. A 70
CM LONG HEVIMET SHADOW BAR PROTECTED THE DETECTORS
FROM THE DIRECT TARGET FLUX. THE SYSTEM COULD BE RO-
TATED ON A CIRCULAR TRACK, AND THE SCATTERING ANGLES
WERE DETERMINED BY MEANS OF A DIGITIZER WITH AN
ANGULAR RESOLUTION OF LESS THAN 0.1 DEGREES.
THE RELATIVE NEUTRON FLUX WAS DETERMINED USING
A TOF NEUTRON MONITOR CONSISTING OF A 5 CM DIAMETER
BY 5 CM THICK FAST PLASTIC SCINTILLATOR COUPLED TO A
FAST PHOTOMULTIPLIER TUBE.
OVERALL UNCERTAINTIES IN THE INDIVIDUAL
CROSS SECTIONS AND IN THE ANGLE INTEGRATED TOTAL
ELASTIC CROSS SECTIONS ARE BETWEEN 4.8 AND 11 PERCENT
AND BELOW 4.8 PERCENT, RESPECTIVELY.
STUDSVIK 6 MV VAN DE GRAAFF ACCELERATOR,
EQUIPPED WITH A TERMINAL PULSING AND KLYSTRON BUNCHING
SYSTEM, AS WELL AS A POST-ACCELERATION BUNCHER.
DELIVERS BURSTS OF IONS AT A REPETITION RATE OF 1 MHZ
WITH A PULSE WIDTH AT HALF MAXIMUM OF LESS THAN 0.3 NS
AND AN AVERAGE BEAM CURRENT OF 3 MICROAMPS.
TARGET CELL OF LENGTH 1.0 CM FILLED WITH TRITIUM
GAS TO A PRESSURE OF UP TO 4.0 ATM. THE MOLYBDENUM
ENTRANCE WINDOW OF THE CELL HAD A THICKNESS OF 4
MG/CM2, AND WAS CLAMPED WITH 0.1 MM THICK INDIUM
O-RINGS BETWEEN SLIGHTLY INCLINED SURFACES. THE TOTAL
ENERGY SPREAD WAS ESTIMATED TO BE LESS THAN +/- 75
KEV.
TIME-OF-FLIGHT. THE TOTAL TIME RESOLUTION WAS
0.7 NS, CORRESPONDING TO AN ENERGY RESOLUTION OF
0.5 MEV.
DIFFERENTIAL CROSS SECTIONS
WERE DETERMINED RELATIVE TO THE N-P SCATTERING CROSS
SECTIONS OF HOPKINS AND BREIT, USING THE LIVERMORE
LRL CONSTRAINED PHASE SHIFTS.
.THE SCATTERING SAMPLES WERE HOLLOW CYLINDERS OF 5.0
CM HEIGHT, OUTER DIAMETER OF 2.5 CM AND INNER DIA-
METER OF 1.0 CM. THEY HAD A NATURAL ELEMENTAL COMPO-
SITION AND A CHEMICAL PURITY CLOSE TO 100 PERCENT.
THE LEAD SAMPLE CONSISTED OF RADIOGENIC LEAD WITH
A COMPOSITION OF 88.2 PERCENT  PB-206
8.8 PERCENT  PB-207
3.0 PERCENT  PB-208.
THE MONITOR SAMPLE WAS A PARALLELEPIPEDIC PIECE OF
POLYETHYLENE WITH THE DIMENSIONS 5.0 X 2.5 X 0.8 CM.
DURING THE EXPERIMENTS THE SAMPLES WERE POSITIONED
AT A DISTANCE OF 14.5 CM IN FRONT OF THE TARGET.
.DATA OBTAINED FROM N.OLSSON 87/10/12.
